# CODEOWNERS — ownership boundary between the governing team and developers.
#
# Mechanism 1 of the governance-authority model (see docs/governance-authority.md).
#
# The paths below define WHO MAY APPROVE A CHANGE, not who may run the code.
# GitHub blocks merging a PR that touches an owned path until a listed owner
# approves it. This puts the authority over governance configuration with the
# governing team even though the controls execute in the agent's process: a
# developer can open a PR that weakens a guard, but they cannot merge it.
#
# Required repo settings for this to have force:
#   - Branch protection on the default branch with "Require review from Code
#     Owners" enabled, and "Allow specified actors to bypass" left empty.
#   - The team handles below must resolve to real GitHub teams. Replace the
#     placeholders before relying on this file.

# ── Default ownership: developers own the application/agent code ──────────────
*                                       @org/agent-developers

# ── Governance authority: the governing team owns every control surface ───────
# The framework-neutral guard pipeline, guards, extensions, and policies.
/governance/                            @org/agent-governance

# The non-overridable runtime floor (mechanism 2). The floor is the root of the
# "config can only tighten" guarantee — it must not be editable by developers.
/governance/floor.py                    @org/agent-governance

# Per-agent governance blocks live inside these YAMLs. Developers legitimately
# tune prompts and a2a limits, but the `governance:` block and the egress
# allow-lists are the governing team's to approve.
/payload_agents/config/                 @org/agent-governance
/cloud_adapters/*/egress.yaml           @org/agent-governance

# The out-of-process egress chokepoint (mechanism 4). The proxy enforces policy
# the agent process cannot alter; its code and IaC are governance-owned.
/cloud_adapters/aws/infra/              @org/agent-governance

# This file and the authority documentation are themselves governance-owned,
# so the ownership boundary cannot be quietly removed in a developer PR.
/.github/CODEOWNERS                     @org/agent-governance
/docs/governance-authority.md           @org/agent-governance
